      <title><![CDATA[Ep.4 Christmas in the collections]]></title>
      <link>https://natlib.govt.nz/blog/posts/ep-4-christmas-in-the-collections</link>
      <description><![CDATA[<i>Celebrating Christmas with poems, a Christmas list, Christmas cards, a menu and a song from the collections . Kia tino ahuareka to Kirihimete | Best of happiness attend thy Christmas.</i>

      <p>Have a listen to us talk about some of the Christmas themed gems we found in the collections.</p>

      <p>If you are interested in more about this topic, we’d recommend <i>A New Zealand Christmas: three centuries of Kiwi Christmas celebrations from the Alexander Turnbull Library</i> by Sarah Ell.</p>
      
      <h3>Mentioned in this podcast</h3>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/records/22299613">Letter to Father Christmas</a> — Edna Crompton's Christmas list written in 1913.</li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/photos?il%5Bcategory%5D=Images&amp;text=father+christmas&amp;commit=Search">Father Christmas visits the Chatham Island</a> — photographs by Duncan Campbell of Father Christmas in the Chathams in 1951.</li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/records/21433307">A New Zealand Christmas three centuries of Kiwi Christmas celebrations from the Alexander Turnbull Library</a> by Sarah Ell</li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AG19121224.2.3.4?items_per_page=10&amp;query=a+health+to+christmas+time+&amp;snippet=true">A Health to Christmas Time</a> — Poem from <em>Ashburton Guardian</em> Volume XXXIII, Issue 8446, 24 December 1912.</li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/records/32044935">Christmas menu 1917</a> — Papers and material relating to soldier's life during World War One. Jeune, Dudley James Frederick, 1897-1949. </li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/GLOBE18750423.2.14?query=The+parson%27s+christmas+dinner+&amp;snippet=true">The Parson's Christmas Dinner</a> — Story from <em>The Globe</em>, Volume III, Issue 270 23 April 1875.</li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/records/22780721">Hands across the sea</a> — New Zealand Postcard published by Frank Duncan &amp; Co., Auckland. 1917.</li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/records/23196732">Māori history, language and culture</a> — record of Matthew Henry Stowell papers, includes list of Christmas and New Year greetings in te reo Māori and English. </li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=muhFfYfWBfw">Star of Wonder</a> — Fred Dagg sing <em>Star of Wonder</em>.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Music references</h3>
      <ul>
      <li>‘<a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/records/40685086">Funiculi Funicula</a>’ — podcast intro theme song. The final track on from Keil Isles album ‘Take Off’.</li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/records/38186371">Abide with me</a> — arranged by William Monk, performed by the National Band of New Zealand in 1953. Closing music in podcast. </li>
      </ul>
      <ul>
      <li>
      <a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/collections/a-z/archive-of-new-zealand-music">Archive of New Zealand Music</a> — the Archive of New Zealand Music is the world's largest archive of unpublished material relating to New Zealand music and musicians</li>
      </ul>

